SUMMARIZER="I">  

The number of tuberculosis (TB) cases among HIV positive patients,
especially drug addicts, has been growing in recent years.  People
with the tuberculosis bacteria ordinarily have only about a 10 per
cent risk of getting active TB; however, HIV, the AIDS virus, weakens
the body's defenses against other diseases and lowers resistance to
the tuberculosis bacteria.  A recent study conducted on 520 drug users
in a methadone program found, during an almost 2-year follow-up, that
eight AIDS-infected people developed active tuberculosis while no
tuberculosis occurred in those who were non- HIV.  Administering the
drug isoniazid prevented tuberculosis development and is now
administered along with the methadone.</SUM>

