According to a study released today which looks at 25,398 nursing home
residents in Arkansas, blacks are twice as likely to get infected with
the tuberculosis (TB) bacteria as whites living under the same
conditions.  Prison data from Arkansas and Minnesota contain the same
conclusion. Overall, blacks suffer six times more TB than whites. Ten
million Americans are infected with the TB bacteria, with about 22,000
active cases and 1,700 deaths reported annually. Additional studies
suggest that whites have evolved better defenses against TB, long
active in Europe, and there is a racial difference in the resistance
of germ-eating blood cells.</SUM>

