The World Health Organization (WHO) claims tuberculosis (TB) is the
world's deadliest infectious disease, annually killing nearly 3
million people worldwide, most between the ages of 15 and 59.  WHO
attributed the rise to the AIDS epidemic, with 3 million people dually
infected.  WHO expects between 15 and 20 million infected with AIDS by
2000, resulting in a sharp rise in TB, a highly communicable disease.
In the U.S., the number of active TB cases is up nearly 5% over the
last year. The 6-month treatment to combat the disease costs $30 to
$50 per person and is not readily available in developing
countries.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910304-0002"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="I">      

The incidence of active tuberculosis cases in New York City rose 38%
in 1990. The city Health Department claims an aggressive attack on
this epidemic.  The Department is testing and treating the homeless,
has established a residence for homeless victims, requires testing of
all children entering school, and is training staffs at homeless and
substance abuse treatment centers in TB prevention and control.  The
TB bacteria is estimated to infect 1,000,000 New Yorkers, but 99% do
not have an active case.  Those with a high risk are people with
defenses weakened by HIV infection, other serious illnesses, or poor
nutrition.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06276078"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="I">      

Poor ventilation systems in modern office buildings are recycling old,
stale air and spreading airborne infections.  Various studies have
found instances where tuberculosis, measles, and flu were spread
throughout sealed, modern office buildings that added little or no
fresh air.  Other places where infections spread rapidly include
airplanes, pediatricians' offices, prisons, hospitals, and homeless
shelters.  Adding 15, or even less than 10, cubic feet per minute of
outdoor air has become common.  Adding even 35 cubic feet per minute
as recommended in Massachusetts would significantly decrease
infection's spread, but can be expensive.</SUM>

